english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Pillow and Stream
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Yom Dong-jeong was in exile, he was transferred to Cheonnyeong County. There he built a pavilion spanning the waters and rested upon it, taking his name from the ancient words of one who would pillow his head on stone and rinse his mouth in the stream. Upon his return, he asked me to write this record.

    I said: "Dong-jeong received the favor of the former king and bowed as minister in his youth. What more need be said of repaying that grace to the present sovereign? He avoided no reproach, refused no hardship. He bore the dark and murky, he steadied the struck and shaken. His vigor is strong as metal and stone, his loyalty moves even spirits—surely he is immovable as the roots of heaven. Though banished to distant places, he preserved his body and kept his life whole, freely enjoying the delights of mountain and water. This is how the king preserved his wish for him—his grace is as vast as heaven itself. How then can he forget this, even at his table or in his rest? Yet from this distant river and lake, he still tends his sovereign's heart. Why then does the pavilion bear a name opposite to this? Does he wish to cleanse his ears so the world's affairs reach him not? Does he wish to purify his body so the dust of the world cannot touch him?"

    Dong-jeong replied: "It is not so. Water by nature is clear. When its essence reaches a man, it penetrates to the bone and chills him—and in that chill, the muddied heart becomes translucent, the restless heart finds stillness. Through this one can serve Heaven, can move the four spirits. Thus Heaven produced water as the first of the five elements, and all things flourish through water's work. Why do people knock on doors morning and evening seeking water and fire? Because neither can be absent even one day—without them, man cannot preserve his life. Water's merit is great. When I speak of using it as a pillow, I mean only to draw near to it—nothing more. This is what I have taken from it."

    I have long heard that among all things between heaven and earth, water is greatest. The earth rests upon water, is borne by water. All things with form and substance in this realm pillow themselves upon water—why should man alone be different? Consider the great mountains towering to heaven: beasts and plants depend upon them to live. Though rain and dew nourish them, if the water-essence did not flow through them, how could life be sustained? The jade well lotus atop Mount Hua stands as proof. How much more so the plains and wide fields, the broken ridges and level forests—where water springs forth by necessity. Thus wherever men dwell, there is no earth without water; whatever men eat, there is no substance without water. That man and water cannot be separated even for a moment is clear.

    Dong-jeong moved from place to place, cultivating himself, his learning renowned throughout his age. In wealth he practiced wealth, in hardship he practiced hardship—such is the depth of what he has attained. I know that when clouds scatter, the moon appears; when water flows, the wind rises. Dong-jeong, serene and solitary, stands apart from the world. What stir could wealth or hardship make upon such a heart?

    This pavilion—through it Heaven shows yet greater kindness to Dong-jeong, extending his influence to all quarters so that our people may wash away their cares and open their spirits, dancing in the highest virtue. This work lies in Heaven's hands. Thus I write this record.
  footnotes:
    - The phrase 'pillow stone and rinse stream' (枕石漱流) derives from the biography of Sun Chuo, a Jin dynasty recluse, suggesting withdrawal from worldly affairs
    - Mount Hua (太華) refers to one of China's sacred peaks; the jade well lotus is a legendary plant symbolizing spiritual purity
    - The 'four spirits' (四靈) are celestial beings in East Asian cosmology; the five elements (五行) are metal, wood, water, fire, and earth, with water considered primary
